Given an upper triangular system with $u_{ii} \neq 0$ for all $i$:
\[
\begin{pmatrix}
u_{11} & u_{12} & \cdots & u_{1n} \\
0 & u_{22} & \cdots & u_{2n} \\
\vdots & & \ddots & \vdots \\
0 & 0 & \cdots & u_{nn}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ \vdots \\ x_n \end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix} c_1 \\ c_2 \\ \vdots \\ c_n \end{pmatrix}
\]

The solution is computed by:
\[
x_n = \frac{c_n}{u_{nn}}, \quad x_i = \frac{c_i - \sum_{j=i+1}^{n} u_{ij}x_j}{u_{ii}} \quad \text{for } i = n-1, \ldots, 1
\]

content.problem:
Consider the system:
\[
\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}
\]

The $(1,1)$ entry is zeroâ€”we cannot compute $m_{21} = a_{21}/a_{11}$. 
Yet the system has a unique solution ($x_1 = 1$, $x_2 = 1$).

**Solution:** Swap rows before eliminating:
\[
\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}
\]

Now back substitution gives: $x_2 = 1$, $x_1 = 2 - 1 = 1$.
